LGR243HB	
While we all prefer US Made products, the competitor to the Rossi, New England Firearms, does not match performance with their single shot rifles against Rossi's in the bean fields of West Tennessee and Northeast Mississippi. From several years of reports from our local customers, the NEF Center Fire single shots produced in the last two decades do not perform as well as their H&R predecessors, and that is also the case against the well made Brazilian Rossi Single Shots. While neither will match a 700 Remington, we're talking about silver dollar or half dollar size groups for the Rossis against cigarette-pack 4-5 inch groups with the NEFs. Our interest in the Rossis takes into account their traditional Brazilian Goncalo hardwood stocks and forends, attractive traditional finishes. Not just those two counts, but also the side mounted lever safeties on the Rossis, and the patented Taurus hammer locks. The flat-faced tempered steel Rossi triggers simply do not exhibit creep and mush like their NEF competitors, and they come with scope mount base included. These specimens are chambered in the venerable and popular .243 Winchester, highly effective on our abundant coyote, deer, and ground hog population, all three the bane of soybean farmers throughout our whole region, more so down in the Delta lands. postcontent: LGRG410B		Not since Winchester / US Repeating Arms closed its doors in early 2006 has there been anything like this on the market. Photos show one of the first specimens we got of Rossi Braztech’s new M830, named model Rio Grande Lever Action Shotgun. Although the history goes all the way back to the Winchester Model of 1883, this Rossi is more heavily indebted to John Marlin than to Oliver Winchester. The Weaver type scope base sitting atop this Rio Grande’s receiver emphasizes that fact as much as anything. That base is removable, of course, and it, the cross-receiver hammer safety, and the 1 inch recoil pad are the only 20th century trappings to this rifle. Styling is traditional repeating or lever action rifle type, only chambered for .410 gauge, 2 1/2 inch, shotshells. Construction is blue steel, and the barrel measures 20 inches, gently rifled for accurate use of slugs, but not enough pronounced rifling to interfere with Shotshells or even buckshot. Company does not advise whether .45 Colt Ammunition is at all feasible; probably not. Capacity is 5 + 1 rounds of .410 gauge, 2 1/2 inch shells; this shotgun is not 3 inch capable. Sights are traditional buckhorn type with step elevator dovetailed-in rear and dovetailed blade front with brass tip. Weight empty is 5.8 pounds, balanced just forward of the lever mount strut on the receiver. Overall length is 38.9 inches, and length of pull is a very adult 13 7/8 inches from the face of the blue steel trigger to the end of the buttpad. Buttstock and forend are traditional walnut-finished Brazilian hardwood. One sees Winchester 9410 shotguns advertised at prices approaching $1500 per unit. title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W .38 Special +P model 442-2 No Lock Airweight Centennial Matte Blue 38 Spl  NIB S&W number 150544 Pre-lock Prelock Style
postcontent:
HG150544
Here is a recent revival of a very popular revolver, not only for both defense minded civilians and law enforcement professionals, but also for those of us who are interested in collectability.  This is the 442-2, named model .38 Centennial Airweight, but its model number should be 442-1, since it is identical to the 442-1 model that enjoyed a production run from 1996, with the introduction of the +P rated J-Magnum frame, until 2002 when the common variant 442-2 with internal lock carried on the matte blue steel and alloy production. Photo specimen shows one from a Smith & Wesson limited run of 442-2 No Locks, Product Code #150544,  furnished with the newer, slicker factory boot type short combat rubber grips presently on almost all lightweight J frames. As far as basic features, the Model 442 is full-time double action; since the hammer is completely enclosed inside the frame. For personal protection, many veteran law enforcement officers and firearms instructors recommend this model 442-2, since the Centennial cannot be fired in single action mode, where a person cocks the hammer and then pulls the trigger. It is an exceedingly dangerous situation when a homeowner hears a noise and immediately backs the hammer on any revolver. This configuration has long been very popular and, in our opinion, vastly less dangerous than many of its semi-automatic peers. In spite of its light weight, it is rated to withstand the pressure from +P, high-velocity proof-load .38 Special ammunition. Furthermore, given the state of the handgun market and consequent prices, we believe the Lightweight J-frame Smith & Wessons are among the best values in firearms. As far as Factory Specs, this revolver is .38 Special +P rated, double action only, 1 7/8 inch barrel, overall length 6 5/16 inches; aluminum alloy small frame J designation; satin stainless finish, Finger Grooved short rubber Boot Grip; serrated ramp front sight with fixed notch rear sight; internal hammer with locking mechanism; .312 width smooth Metal Injected Molded trigger; 5 shot capacity. title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W .38 Special +P Talo Special Edition Centennial Airweight 642-2 Stainless NIB 38 Spl 150957  Combat Grips 38 Spl Model 642
postcontent:
HG150957
  Revolver in the photo is one of only a few special edition variants of the S&W .38 Centennial Airweight Stainless. This a Talo special number, SKU 150957. Its grips are specially cut dark black gray laminate, somewhat on the order of the classic combat grips of the 1980s. This revolver left the factory on January 18, 2011. The named model of the revolver itself, of course, comes from its ancestor, the .38 Centennial Airweight introduced in the Company’s Centennial Year of 1952, a popular product descended from the experimental Air Crewman all-aluminum revolver of the early 1950s. Barrel, cylinder and parts are all stainless steel, integrated into a lightweight aluminum alloy frame, hence the 15 ounce light weight empty, down from 20-21 ounces for the steel J frame Smith & Wessons. The Centennial was introduced as a pocket revolver. Since its hammer is completely encased in the frame, there is no possibility of clothing snagging from the hammer spur. Action, then, is double action only; there is no way for the hammer to stand in single action. A distinct advantage to the Centennial is that an alarmed, armed homeowner will not be able to cock the revolver into single action when he or she hears a noise; but a steady deliberate pull of the trigger will fire the revolver with more certainty than any automatic ever produced. Smith & Wesson revolvers all have an internal transfer bar safety to guard against accidental discharge, and this 642-2 variant has the internal hammer lock, supplied with two keys, that puts it in compliance with all state laws, at least for the time being. The special edition grips allow a firm hold with minimal increase of the overall height or size of the small J frame. They are some of the most attractive, good feeling, and positive gripping stocks ever sold for the J Frame. Replacement price on these revolvers is now upwards of $600.00 in our area, if a person can even find one. postcontent:
HG163070
This is the faintly modified descendant of the 1955 Smith & Wesson Airweight Bodyguard, the model 638-3, current production 5-shot lightweight stainless .38 Special with the classic 2 inch barrel. With considerable demand for pocket revolvers in the 1950s, Smith & Wesson introduced its Centennial Model in 1952, but there was still demand for a pocket lightweight .38 that a person could still fire in single action mode, like the Airweight Chief's Special, only without the hammer spur snagging a person's pocket or purse upon drawing the weapon. The upper part of the frame, as the photos show, shield the hammer; but still exposes its cleat-serrated hammer spur enough to produce a cocking motion for precise single action firing. The lightweight stainless variant of the Airweight Bodyguard, the 638, was introduced as a limited run in 1989, then added as a regular part of the Smith & Wesson line in 1996, when Smith & Wesson beefed up the J-frame sufficiently for it to handle High Performance +P ammunition. This third, current variant of the 638 has a .312 MIM Metal-injected-Molded .312 smooth combat trigger and MIM flat-faced hammer with floating firing pin. All S&W Revolvers have an internal transfer bar safety that prevents accidental firing if a loaded weapon is dropped, and in 2002, the 638-3 entered the market with Smith & Wesson's patented internal lock. Barrel length is 1 7/8 inches, and this 5 shot pocket revolver only weighs 14 5/8 ounces empty. Grips are Smith & Wesson's new boot grip, softer rubber panels that give a surer grip without increasing the dimensions of the revolver. Smith & Wesson Product Code is 163070. These revolvers have always been fairly scarce, hardly ever more so than nowadays. Replacement price on them in our area, if a person can find one, is upwards of $600.00. title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W .38 Special +P Centennial Airweight 642-2 Stainless NIB 38 Spl 163810
postcontent:
HG163810
Revolver in the photo is the most current configuration of the S&W .38 Centennial Airweight Stainless. Its name, of course, comes from its ancestor, the .38 Centennial Airweight introduced in the Company’s Centennial Year of 1952, a popular product descended from the experimental Air Crewman all-aluminum revolver of the early 1950s. Barrel, cylinder and parts are all stainless steel, integrated into a lightweight aluminum alloy frame, hence the 15 ounce light weight empty, down from 20-21 ounces for the steel J frame Smith & Wessons. The Centennial was introduced as a pocket revolver. Since its hammer is completely encased in the frame, there is no possibility of clothing snagging from the hammer spur. Action, then, is double action only; there is no way for the hammer to stand in single action. A distinct advantage to the Centennial is that an alarmed, armed homeowner will not be able to cock the revolver into single action when he or she hears a noise; but a steady deliberate pull of the trigger will fire the revolver with more certainty than any automatic ever produced. Smith & Wesson revolvers all have an internal transfer bar safety to guard against accidental discharge, and this 642-2 variant has the internal hammer lock, supplied with two keys, that puts it in compliance with all state laws, at least for the time being. Note the new-design Smith & Wesson factory boot grips that allow a firm hold without increasing the height or size of the small J frame. These revolvers also come in the new strong Smith & Wesson one piece boxes. Replacement price on these revolvers is now upwards of $600.00 in our area, if a person can even find one. postcontent:
LGSG1060N	

Actually a better gun than the old 1887 Remington that it was cloned from, this Norinco / Century Arms Coach gun is all blue steel, very sturdy, with American Walnut stock and forend. Barrels are 20 inch Cylinder Bore, wide open, and this shotgun has a tang safety as well as half-cock position for its hammers. We have sold China made Shotguns, Jin An and Norinco, now for over 20 years with excellent service experience, and we commend our Chinese friends on their expertise and workmanship on firearms. We refrain, however, from complimenting their packaging, normally any given one of these shotguns will have some sort of minor cosmetic flaw like the small dimple visible in the photo of the left side of the buttstock near the comb. These factors explain why this shotgun is $300 range, and its Italian competitors twice that much. These fine little shotguns weigh in at a healthy 8 pounds or so. Barrels are 20 inch blue steel, 2 3/4 inch chambers, Full Choke Right tube and Modified Left tube. The specimens we have miked gauge at .698 right tube and .685 left tube, definitely not for steel shot loads. Buttstock length of pull including their 3/8 inch thick rubber recoil pad is the standard 14 inches. While these are immensely popular in cowboy action shooting circles, they are also a fearsome weapon in their own right, always have been. title: For Sale:  HK P30 9mm
postcontent: I am selling my 95-98% Condition HK P30 V3 (DA/SA) 9mm pistol.  This was my first handgun that I purchased and I love it, the grip truly feels like a glove.  That is because it has not only an adjustable back strap, but also adjustable side panels that allow the handgun to truly form to your individual hand.  This gun is also completely ambidextrous, with a paddle mag release, a slide release on each side of the frame, plus a decocker that is located on the rear of the gun, just push it down and the hammer safety falls forward.  The P30 also has a true picatinny rail for lights and/or lasers.  This gun is crazy accurate and light on the recoil, which allows for fast follow-up shots.  The trigger is broken in and the pull weight has been slightly reduced due to use, but honestly that is a good thing... the DA pull was about 10-11 lbs, now it is probably 8-9 lbs and very smooth.  The single action is probably lighter too, but its breaking point is so awesome that it is hard to tell the trigger pull is better.  I would say the SA pull is probably still around 4-5 lbs, and breaks crisp.  There is some play before that point, but once it is there, it is AWESOME!!! The gun comes with TWO 15 round magazines, the original box, factory spent casing, manual, HK lock, and all side panels and back straps.  The only thing to note is that this HK has the "glow in the dark" sights, these are (in my opinion) better than standard dot sights, but obviously not as good as true night sights.  The only true reason I am even getting rid of this handgun is because I am now using 45acp handguns only and dont use this at all anymore.  If I dont have a practical use for it, then I want to find someone that will truly enjoy it as much as I have.  Requirements for purchase; FTF purchase within an hour away from Clarksville/Jeffersonville area (I may make exceptions), must show that you have Indiana ID and gun permit, have no felonies, and be willing to sign "bill of sale".  If you have any other questions just contact me through here and we can work something out. Not really interested in too many things to trade (I would rather sell the handgun), but willing to hear similar quality trade offers (Sigs, 1911s with light rails, anything 45acp), but if anything a high end AK74 in 5.45x39 (slr 105, etc) +/- extra depending on quality and condition would be awesome.
